of caught my eye.

00:06:16.780 --> 00:06:19.500
More recently on discussions
about food waste,

00:06:19.500 --> 00:06:21.130
the USDA issued this report.

00:06:21.130 --> 00:06:23.750
This is only about a
month old actually.

00:06:23.750 --> 00:06:27.350
And their look back
report, going back to 2010,

00:06:27.350 --> 00:06:29.560
is just plain frightening.

00:06:29.560 --> 00:06:35.600
In 2010, America lost $161
billion worth of food,

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:36.210
in one year.

00:06:36.210 --> 00:06:40.240
We talk about our budget,
how it affects the economy.

00:06:40.240 --> 00:06:42.804
Imagine if somebody had
to write a check for $161

00:06:42.804 --> 00:06:43.470
billion dollars.

00:06:43.470 --> 00:06:46.810
We flush that away
in food waste.

00:06:46.810 --> 00:06:49.360
A third of our food
didn't get consumed.

00:06:49.360 --> 00:06:51.120
And that's a significant
chunk of what

00:06:51.120 --> 00:06:54.680
we could have been giving people
across America as the nutrition

00:06:54.680 --> 00:06:56.780
that they need.

00:06:56.780 --> 00:07:00.070
In 2012, the National
Resource Defense Counsel

00:07:00.070 --> 00:07:01.070
issued this report.

00:07:01.070 --> 00:07:04.880
Now although the report
came before the USDA report,

00:07:04.880 --> 00:07:06.180
it's actually using later data.

00:07:06.180 --> 00:07:08.200
So the two of them
swap a little bit.

00:07:08.200 --> 00:07:10.750
Their computations
were 40% of the food

00:07:10.750 --> 00:07:12.940
in this country is not consumed.

00:07:12.940 --> 00:07:16.940
4% of the energy American
reduces got lost.

00:07:16.940 --> 00:07:20.610
32% of the water
we have was wasted.

00:07:20.610 --> 00:07:23.080
Because water is a
huge part of our-- use

00:07:23.080 --> 00:07:24.620
of water for agriculture.

00:07:24.620 --> 00:07:27.810
And it represented about
20 pounds a person, of food

00:07:27.810 --> 00:07:29.100
a month.

00:07:29.100 --> 00:07:33.680
So this is hurting everybody
across the country.

00:07:33.680 --> 00:07:35.190
This is from that NRDC report.

00:07:35.190 --> 00:07:37.900
I'd like you to focus for
a minute on the large red

00:07:37.900 --> 00:07:39.560
and green pies on there.

00:07:39.560 --> 00:07:43.210
That's fruit and vegetables,
in billions of pounds.

00:07:43.210 --> 00:07:47.320
So looking at about 18 and
1/2 billion pounds of fruit,

00:07:47.320 --> 00:07:50.110
about 25 billion pounds of
vegetables that didn't get

00:07:50.110 --> 00:07:50.610
consumed.

00:07:53.790 --> 00:07:56.130
We all own this problem.

00:07:56.130 --> 00:07:57.760
As I said, it
starts at the farm,

00:07:57.760 --> 00:07:59.290
and it ends at
the kitchen table.

00:07:59.290 --> 00:08:02.950
Everybody has a piece
of this problem.

00:08:02.950 --> 00:08:06.530
What was not in any of
these reports however,

00:08:06.530 --> 00:08:08.470
were the people like
myself, and maybe

00:08:08.470 --> 00:08:11.820
like you, who are home
and community gardeners.

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:14.570
No one's ever really looked at
that information in any detail,

00:08:14.570 --> 00:08:17.000
about the food that
we have, and the food

00:08:17.000 --> 00:08:18.930
that we're not actually using.

00:08:18.930 --> 00:08:20.850
The National
Gardening Association

00:08:20.850 --> 00:08:23.660
issued a report very recently.

00:08:23.660 --> 00:08:27.790
And we're now up to 42 million
people in this country growing

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:29.267
food in home and
community gardens.

00:08:29.267 --> 00:08:31.850
That's about a little more than
a third of all the households.

00:08:31.850 --> 00:08:34.580
To 17% in the past five years.

00:08:34.580 --> 00:08:36.929
And most interestingly,
the average gardener

00:08:36.929 --> 00:08:39.630
harvests about 300
pounds of food a year.

00:08:39.630 --> 00:08:42.020
Now it's not 300 pounds
over the course of a year,

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:44.169
because we don't grow
over the course of a year.

00:08:44.169 --> 00:08:46.080
That's compressed into
your growing season.

00:08:46.080 --> 00:08:47.860
So you're waiting for
maybe nine months.

00:08:47.860 --> 00:08:49.040
And then in three
months, you're dealing

00:08:49.040 --> 00:08:50.716
with a staggering
amount of food,

00:08:50.716 --> 00:08:52.840
which is typically more
than you can use, preserve,

00:08:52.840 --> 00:08:54.310
or you can share with friends.

00:08:54.310 --> 00:08:56.070
This is not just in the suburbs.

00:08:56.070 --> 00:08:58.070
An increasing amount of
people in urban settings

00:08:58.070 --> 00:08:59.220
are growing food.

00:08:59.220 --> 00:09:01.444
And even in the younger
generation, Millennials,

00:09:01.444 --> 00:09:02.860
it's a huge increase
in the number

00:09:02.860 --> 00:09:05.040
of people who are growing
food for themselves.

00:09:05.040 --> 00:09:06.910
The food waste on
the grower side

00:09:06.910 --> 00:09:10.379
comes from enthusiasm,
over planting,

00:09:10.379 --> 00:09:11.920
not being able to
share with friends,

00:09:11.920 --> 00:09:13.940
I've discovered personally--
there's only so many cucumbers

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:16.106
you can give to friends and
still have them call you

00:09:16.106 --> 00:09:16.980
a friend.

00:09:16.980 --> 00:09:19.030
Choosing not to preserve in can.

00:09:19.030 --> 00:09:20.660
And just getting
bored and overwhelmed,

00:09:20.660 --> 00:09:23.370
come August and September, the
tomatoes are still producing,

00:09:23.370 --> 00:09:24.500
and you're fed up.

00:09:24.500 --> 00:09:29.310
The stuff is left to rot,
or goes into the garbage.

00:09:29.310 --> 00:09:31.360
So what's the impact
of this food waste?

00:09:34.280 --> 00:09:35.520
This is not a political map.

00:09:35.520 --> 00:09:36.780
Let me start with this.

00:09:36.780 --> 00:09:38.690
Those red states,
these 23 states,

00:09:38.690 --> 00:09:40.980
if you add the combined
population of the states,

00:09:40.980 --> 00:09:42.770
you're looking at
the number of people

00:09:42.770 --> 00:09:44.770
in this country who
are food insecure.

00:09:44.770 --> 00:09:46.610
Food insecurity, by
the way, means either

00:09:46.610 --> 00:09:49.780
that you're hungry, or you're
at real risk of being hungry.

00:09:49.780 --> 00:09:54.370
So one out of every six Americas
are considered food insecure.

00:09:54.370 --> 00:09:56.590
That's about 50 million people.

00:09:56.590 --> 00:09:59.825
One out of every four
children in this country

00:09:59.825 --> 00:10:01.450
are growing up in a
food insecure home.

00:10:01.450 --> 00:10:02.824
And in some
populations, it's one

00:10:02.824 --> 00:10:06.440
out of every three children.

00:10:06.440 --> 00:10:09.760
These kids who don't eat
well, don't do well in school.

00:10:09.760 --> 00:10:11.580
Their parents, who
don't eat well,

00:10:11.580 --> 00:10:13.580
don't do well in the workplace.

00:10:13.580 --> 00:10:17.450
So the country is hurting,
today's economy and tomorrow's

00:10:17.450 --> 00:10:19.650
economy, by not
nourishing the people

00:10:19.650 --> 00:10:22.160
that need the food the most.

00:10:22.160 --> 00:10:24.790
The impact from the health
perspective is staggering.

00:10:24.790 --> 00:10:27.850
People are arguing about
the Affordable Health Care

00:10:27.850 --> 00:10:29.270
Act, Obamacare.

00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:31.640
Really what's
coming down the pike

00:10:31.640 --> 00:10:35.460
are staggering numbers on
obesity, type 2 diabetes,

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:37.940
hypertension, and other
food related illnesses.

00:10:37.940 --> 00:10:40.730
Things that we could
prevent and actually fix,

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:42.414
are trending to the worst.

00:10:42.414 --> 00:10:43.830
In part because
of the food that's

00:10:43.830 --> 00:10:46.840
available to too many people.

00:10:46.840 --> 00:10:50.910
I had a brief chat with General
Clark in October, retired.

00:10:50.910 --> 00:10:52.620
Three out of four
young people who

00:10:52.620 --> 00:10:54.040
apply to the
military service are

00:10:54.040 --> 00:10:57.820
rejected, because
they're not fit to serve.

00:10:57.820 --> 00:10:59.670
How does the food
system work today?

00:10:59.670 --> 00:11:01.590
The food safety net,
the food bank system.

00:11:01.590 --> 00:11:04.256
If you look at the chart, let me
see if the pointers is working.

00:11:04.256 --> 00:11:05.440
It does, all right.

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:08.460
The red dot in the middle
is feeding America.

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:11.020
That is an organization
that represents

00:11:11.020 --> 00:11:14.720
and sort of coordinates 203
food banks across America.

00:11:14.720 --> 00:11:17.440
Food banks being large
warehouse type operations,

00:11:17.440 --> 00:11:19.760
that collect and
redistribute food.

00:11:19.760 --> 00:11:23.590
They connect to 33,500 food
pantries, soup Kitchens,

00:11:23.590 --> 00:11:25.620
and other similar, food
distribution agencies

00:11:25.620 --> 00:11:27.210
across the country.

00:11:27.210 --> 00:11:30.340
That system works very
nicely for processed food.

00:11:30.340 --> 00:11:32.200
You want to have
bread, corn flakes,

00:11:32.200 --> 00:11:35.900
things-- works
very, very nicely.

00:11:35.900 --> 00:11:38.780
One of the problems, is
however, the distribution cycle.

00:11:38.780 --> 00:11:41.550
If you look at that red line
on the bottom marked time,

00:11:41.550 --> 00:11:43.950
it can take days
or weeks for food

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:48.130
to move from that food
bank to a food pantry.

00:11:48.130 --> 00:11:50.320
The result is, that while
processed canned jars,

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:53.120
boxes work fine, fresh
food doesn't work,.

00:11:53.120 --> 00:11:56.630
Which is why, when you go to a
food drive, you're always told,

00:11:56.630 --> 00:12:00.160
jars, cans, boxes--
no fresh food.

00:12:00.160 --> 00:12:02.970
The result is that 42
million people like myself,

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:04.530
who grow food in
home gardens often

00:12:04.530 --> 00:12:06.340
end up just tossing it away.

00:12:06.340 --> 00:12:07.590
If it's more than you can use.

00:12:07.590 --> 00:12:10.710
You either compost it, or
worse, it goes into a landfill,

00:12:10.710 --> 00:12:14.080
and creates
environmental problems.

00:12:14.080 --> 00:12:17.440
In March 2009, I had an idea.

00:12:17.440 --> 00:12:21.770
The idea was, what if we
could enable these people have

00:12:21.770 --> 00:12:24.360
too much food in
their home gardens--

00:12:24.360 --> 00:12:27.281
myself included, by the way--
to be able to donate food

00:12:27.281 --> 00:12:29.280
to the people in the
community who most need it.

00:12:29.280 --> 00:12:31.430
This came out of a discussion
I had in the community garden

00:12:31.430 --> 00:12:32.013
I was running.

00:12:32.013 --> 00:12:33.430
I said to these
people, if you're

00:12:33.430 --> 00:12:35.120
going to have an ample
harvest, the least we could do

00:12:35.120 --> 00:12:36.203
is give it away to people.

00:12:36.203 --> 00:12:37.740
It just rolled off my tongue.

00:12:37.740 --> 00:12:39.350
That was another tipping point.

00:12:39.350 --> 00:12:40.975
Because I found an
AmpleHarvest.org was

00:12:40.975 --> 00:12:43.740
an available domain,
so I grabbed it.

00:12:43.740 --> 00:12:45.380
I had spent the
$9 on that, and I

00:12:45.380 --> 00:12:46.630
couldn't let that go to waste.

00:12:46.630 --> 00:12:47.830
So that brought me to here.

00:12:50.410 --> 00:12:53.850
The idea was to enable
the food to be donated,

00:12:53.850 --> 00:12:57.560
and nobody had ever really done
that before, on a large scale.

00:12:57.560 --> 00:12:59.460
But the vision I
had, the idea was,

00:12:59.460 --> 00:13:01.414
let's bypass the
choke point, and let's

00:13:01.414 --> 00:13:02.830
get that food
directly to the food

00:13:02.830 --> 00:13:05.310
pantries in the communities.

00:13:05.310 --> 00:13:07.571
Because the food-- you can
live in northern Vermont,

00:13:07.571 --> 00:13:09.820
and be a three hour drive
from the regional food bank.

00:13:09.820 --> 00:13:11.800
Or you could go down the
street or across town,

00:13:11.800 --> 00:13:13.770
to the nearby food pantry.

00:13:13.770 --> 00:13:16.710
So that's how AmpleHarvest.org
was actually born.

00:13:16.710 --> 00:13:21.130
The idea was to both be a in the
cloud registry of food pantries

00:13:21.130 --> 00:13:23.089
across America-- an opt-in
registry by the way.

00:13:23.089 --> 00:13:24.546
This is something
where each pantry

00:13:24.546 --> 00:13:25.970
says we want to
be a part of this.

00:13:25.970 --> 00:13:27.815
And a search engine.

00:13:27.815 --> 00:13:29.567
And by the way, Google
was an inspiration

00:13:29.567 --> 00:13:31.900
from that perspective in my
mind, for how to build this.

00:13:31.900 --> 00:13:34.010
A search engine to
actually find the food

00:13:34.010 --> 00:13:35.480
pantries in your neighborhood.

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:38.540
And then for you to actually
take the food directly

00:13:38.540 --> 00:13:39.830
to the food pantry yourself.

00:13:39.830 --> 00:13:40.750
Were not involved.

00:13:40.750 --> 00:13:42.420
So we have zero logistics.

00:13:42.420 --> 00:13:44.690
The hope and the intent was
to create a system whereby

00:13:44.690 --> 00:13:47.210
once you knew you could and
should donate the food--

00:13:47.210 --> 00:13:49.479
and we enabled it--
you would do so

00:13:49.479 --> 00:13:50.770
for the rest of gardening life.

00:13:50.770 --> 00:13:52.300
And on top of that, you
would tell your friends

00:13:52.300 --> 00:13:54.925
who are complaining that they've
grown too much food, that they

00:13:54.925 --> 00:13:59.280
had the opportunity
to donate the food.

00:13:59.280 --> 00:14:01.870
This is what AmpleHarvest.org
looks like today.

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:03.575
It's looks very
familiar for those

00:14:03.575 --> 00:14:04.950
of you familiar
with Google Maps.

00:14:04.950 --> 00:14:06.350
It's basically a search engine.

00:14:06.350 --> 00:14:07.641
There's a database of pantries.

00:14:07.641 --> 00:14:09.380
You pick the pantry
that you want.

00:14:09.380 --> 00:14:11.150
You find the pantry,
and now you've

00:14:11.150 --> 00:14:13.660
got a direct connection
with that food pantry.

00:14:13.660 --> 00:14:16.030
One of the pantries did
something I hadn't expected.

00:14:16.030 --> 00:14:17.500
It was His Hands Food Pantry.

00:14:17.500 --> 00:14:19.120
This particular
pantry registered

00:14:19.120 --> 00:14:22.034
and they did something in their
listing I haven't expected.

00:14:22.034 --> 00:14:23.950
They talk back to the
community and said, hey,

00:14:23.950 --> 00:14:26.330
we need stuff from you.

00:14:26.330 --> 00:14:27.790
It was the first
time I saw that.

00:14:27.790 --> 00:14:29.270
And it dawned on me,
my god, these pantries

00:14:29.270 --> 00:14:30.710
are talking back
to the community.

00:14:30.710 --> 00:14:33.704
They're telling the community
what they really need.

00:14:33.704 --> 00:14:35.495
That created a whole
new market efficiency,

00:14:35.495 --> 00:14:37.825
and we're building the new
AmpleHarvest.org you'll

00:14:37.825 --> 00:14:39.950
be learning about in a few
minutes, around the idea

00:14:39.950 --> 00:14:41.366
that not only can
you donate food,

00:14:41.366 --> 00:14:43.580
but the pantries can
actually help guide you

00:14:43.580 --> 00:14:45.580
to what they most
importantly need.

00:14:45.580 --> 00:14:48.820
So the innovations are all over
the place, as it turned out.

00:14:48.820 --> 00:14:51.029
I built this and then I
looked back and said, my god,

00:14:51.029 --> 00:14:52.820
look at all these things
that are in there.

00:14:52.820 --> 00:14:54.030
The food system gets improve.

00:14:54.030 --> 00:14:55.310
Behavior gets changed.

00:14:55.310 --> 00:14:57.810
The environment is
impacted, and the impact

00:14:57.810 --> 00:14:59.460
on society as a
whole, has changed.

00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:03.010
But basically, it's a very
empowering resource for anybody

00:15:03.010 --> 00:15:05.190
to be able to go,
and to say, I can

00:15:05.190 --> 00:15:07.650
be the game changer
for my own community.

00:15:07.650 --> 00:15:10.020
For the first time, food
pantries across America,

00:15:10.020 --> 00:15:12.417
that almost never
have fresh food,

00:15:12.417 --> 00:15:14.000
suddenly began to
have the opportunity

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:16.140
to offer fresh
food to the people

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:17.770
in their own communities.

00:15:17.770 --> 00:15:21.410
This is in Bridgeport,
Connecticut.

00:15:21.410 --> 00:15:23.160
It's an urban city.

00:15:23.160 --> 00:15:26.950
Somebody donated food that
would have been thrown away,

00:15:26.950 --> 00:15:28.230
to a food pantry.

00:15:28.230 --> 00:15:30.000
Just imagine what
that type of change

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:32.041
that happens, whether
you're in Bridgeport or New

00:15:32.041 --> 00:15:34.790
York, or near the city or
suburb, or rural setting.

00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:37.310
It works all over.

00:15:37.310 --> 00:15:41.200
So AmpleHarvest.org, I had
this idea in March of 2009,

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:46.499
and it took me seven weeks from
that idea date to get it built.

00:15:46.499 --> 00:15:47.540
And to get it rolled out.

00:15:47.540 --> 00:15:49.873
And by the way, at the time
it was done by three people.

00:15:49.873 --> 00:15:53.510
A woman who donated her time
in town for the front end

00:15:53.510 --> 00:15:55.500
of the pretty part,
where it looks good.

00:15:55.500 --> 00:15:58.950
A gentleman who put together his
time for building the database.

00:15:58.950 --> 00:16:00.240
And I did the contents.

00:16:00.240 --> 00:16:02.280
So basically, if it's
pretty, Maureen did it.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:03.630
If it's data, Josh did it.

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:05.330
And if you can
read it, I did it.

00:16:05.330 --> 00:16:07.770
Once it was put together
and we were at this point,

00:16:07.770 --> 00:16:09.670
the first pantry signed up.

00:16:09.670 --> 00:16:12.260
I started making heavy
use if Google Alerts,

00:16:12.260 --> 00:16:15.000
to start telling me about other
pantries and other connections,

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.630
to start spreading the word.

00:16:17.630 --> 00:16:20.630
This was 100
pantries on June 20.

00:16:20.630 --> 00:16:24.400
Now what's interesting is that
I had gone to Google and said,

00:16:24.400 --> 00:16:26.450
do you guys have anything
you can help us with?

00:16:26.450 --> 00:16:28.140
I got this really cool idea.

00:16:28.140 --> 00:16:30.180
And the answer was yes.

00:16:30.180 --> 00:16:31.900
Google has an AdWords
grant program.

00:16:31.900 --> 00:16:32.530
We applied.

00:16:32.530 --> 00:16:35.000
We got fast tracked through
that system really fast,

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:37.320
and whoever I owe
thanks to, thank you.

00:16:37.320 --> 00:16:40.400
And so in the time between
launch and this date,

00:16:40.400 --> 00:16:43.410
AmpleHarvest.org was
already up on AdWords.

00:16:43.410 --> 00:16:45.750
And I have to say, I knew
nothing about AdWords myself.

00:16:45.750 --> 00:16:47.490
It was a quick learn
I had to go through.

00:16:47.490 --> 00:16:48.948
And at this point,
AmpleHarvest.org

00:16:48.948 --> 00:16:52.680
was now a one person
operation, largely me.

00:16:52.680 --> 00:16:54.740
This is 500 pantries in August.

00:16:54.740 --> 00:16:57.300
We had 1,000 pantries
in October, 2015,

00:16:57.300 --> 00:16:59.440
which just happened
to be World Food Day.

00:16:59.440 --> 00:17:06.780
2,000 pantries, and today, we're
at nearly 7,000 food pantries.

00:17:06.780 --> 00:17:09.030
One out of every
five in America.

00:17:09.030 --> 00:17:12.349
This means that people who
live in these communities,

00:17:12.349 --> 00:17:14.900
for the first time ever,
are able to donate food

00:17:14.900 --> 00:17:18.520
to a food pantry in
their own community.

00:17:18.520 --> 00:17:22.619
Media coverage went off
the roof, it was wonderful.

00:17:22.619 --> 00:17:25.180
Instead of food going
into a waste stream,

00:17:25.180 --> 00:17:28.079
people were donating
food from home gardens

00:17:28.079 --> 00:17:29.970
Small farmers were
donating food,

00:17:29.970 --> 00:17:31.794
and it was getting
into the pantry system.

00:17:31.794 --> 00:17:33.210
And by the way,
just so everybody,

00:17:33.210 --> 00:17:34.980
knows the feedback
from the pantries

00:17:34.980 --> 00:17:37.490
has been that when the
fresh food shows up,

00:17:37.490 --> 00:17:39.542
it's the first thing
the clients go for.

00:17:39.542 --> 00:17:41.000
I mean there's been
this idea that,

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:42.490
do people really
want fresh food?

00:17:42.490 --> 00:17:43.490
They do.

00:17:43.490 --> 00:17:46.140
And it's the first
that they go for.

00:17:46.140 --> 00:17:49.780
So for the future,
you're looking

00:17:49.780 --> 00:17:51.270
at the new AmpleHarvest.org.

