unpunished sort of idea.

00:22:29.360 --> 00:22:30.860
And that is that,
I've discovered

00:22:30.860 --> 00:22:33.780
that in the nonprofit world,
great ideas don't receive quite

00:22:33.780 --> 00:22:36.210
the reception they receive
in the for-profit world.

00:22:36.210 --> 00:22:38.380
So what we've discovered--
it's been interesting,

00:22:38.380 --> 00:22:41.130
is that when you
have a new idea,

00:22:41.130 --> 00:22:42.600
people look it the old way.

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:45.810
The typical food bank model
is, how many pounds of food?

00:22:45.810 --> 00:22:47.920
How many meals did you serve?

00:22:47.920 --> 00:22:49.880
That really doesn't work here.

00:22:49.880 --> 00:22:52.590
And as a matter of
fact, here, this

00:22:52.590 --> 00:22:55.060
is the questions that we
realize become really important.

00:22:55.060 --> 00:22:56.420
And I did a thought
experiment, by the way,

00:22:56.420 --> 00:22:57.420
that brought me to this.

00:22:57.420 --> 00:22:59.790
Because I originally thought
this was a hunger program.

00:22:59.790 --> 00:23:02.277
It was, the obvious thing to
me was, we're feeding people.

00:23:02.277 --> 00:23:04.110
So I have this very
quick thought experiment

00:23:04.110 --> 00:23:06.510
I want to do with all
of you for a minute.

00:23:06.510 --> 00:23:08.365
Imagine every food
pantry in America--

00:23:08.365 --> 00:23:12.430
all 33,500 are on
AmpleHarvest.org.

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:16.130
And imagine every grower
in America-- all 42 million

00:23:16.130 --> 00:23:19.690
knew about their
opportunity to donate food.

00:23:19.690 --> 00:23:23.950
And imagine if there was
a drought or a blight,

00:23:23.950 --> 00:23:26.540
and every garden
in America died,

00:23:26.540 --> 00:23:30.870
nothing was harvested that
year, are we a success,

00:23:30.870 --> 00:23:33.470
is AmpleHarvest.org a
success or a failure?

00:23:33.470 --> 00:23:36.095
So a show of hands, how many say
AmpleHarvest.org is a success?

00:23:39.390 --> 00:23:41.790
How many say failure?

00:23:41.790 --> 00:23:44.040
All right, you had the
same idea that I had.

00:23:44.040 --> 00:23:46.230
The fact that the
food wasn't, couldn't

00:23:46.230 --> 00:23:48.090
be moved, had nothing
to do with us.

00:23:48.090 --> 00:23:51.040
We had set up the conduit
for the food to move.

00:23:51.040 --> 00:23:52.790
And that's where I
came to the realization

00:23:52.790 --> 00:23:54.206
that the heart of
AmpleHarvest.org

00:23:54.206 --> 00:23:57.070
is not so much feeding people,
but getting people fed.

00:23:57.070 --> 00:23:59.760
It's a supply side channel
for the food bank system.

00:23:59.760 --> 00:24:01.445
Once I got to that
realization-- this

00:24:01.445 --> 00:24:03.570
has been part of this
problem of being in the weeds

00:24:03.570 --> 00:24:04.920
and not being in the
forest, I started

00:24:04.920 --> 00:24:06.503
to understand the
really bigger impact

00:24:06.503 --> 00:24:07.930
of what this program
is all about.

00:24:07.930 --> 00:24:10.340
And the people who are working
on it, what we all share.

00:24:10.340 --> 00:24:12.340
That red dot in
that orange circle

00:24:12.340 --> 00:24:15.310
represents a single soup
kitchen Washington, DC.

00:24:15.310 --> 00:24:18.309
9 mile radius circle
around it, 250 square miles

00:24:18.309 --> 00:24:19.850
and the question
is, how many growers

00:24:19.850 --> 00:24:21.840
live in 250 square miles?

00:24:21.840 --> 00:24:24.430
Depends on where you are,
but you know it's not zero.

00:24:24.430 --> 00:24:26.420
We've created the
opportunity for those growers

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:28.490
to donate food to that pantry.

00:24:28.490 --> 00:24:30.830
And then look how many dots
are on the map right now.

00:24:30.830 --> 00:24:34.080
That's the amount of opportunity
that AmpleHarvest.org now

00:24:34.080 --> 00:24:36.370
represents, and
growing, to change

00:24:36.370 --> 00:24:38.620
the future of the country.

00:24:38.620 --> 00:24:40.907
The problem was-- and
a more interesting one,

00:24:40.907 --> 00:24:42.490
from the support
perspective, in terms

00:24:42.490 --> 00:24:44.420
of getting funding
from foundations.

00:24:44.420 --> 00:24:48.970
Your typical food
funding organization,

00:24:48.970 --> 00:24:51.630
working with a food
organization, works like this.

00:24:51.630 --> 00:24:55.320
They ask for $100 thousand,
$10,000 goes operation.

00:24:55.320 --> 00:24:56.949
$90,000 goes to food.

00:24:56.949 --> 00:24:58.740
You feed the families,
you run out of food,

00:24:58.740 --> 00:24:59.470
you come back again.

00:24:59.470 --> 00:25:00.428
You ask for more money.

00:25:00.428 --> 00:25:02.154
And that loop goes
on and on and on.

00:25:02.154 --> 00:25:03.570
And your bean
counters look at it,

00:25:03.570 --> 00:25:05.520
and they say, wow,
only 10% overhead,

00:25:05.520 --> 00:25:06.910
that's really kind of cool.

00:25:06.910 --> 00:25:08.890
Go with it.

00:25:08.890 --> 00:25:11.860
Then a scrappy young nonprofit
comes along and says,

00:25:11.860 --> 00:25:14.480
well, we don't need the
$90 thousand for the food.

00:25:14.480 --> 00:25:15.980
The food's already
in the community.

00:25:15.980 --> 00:25:20.850
We do need money for staff and
technology, so $10,000 please.

00:25:20.850 --> 00:25:23.090
You look at it first,
you say $10,000

00:25:23.090 --> 00:25:25.166
to permanently fix a
system that doesn't

00:25:25.166 --> 00:25:27.290
need to be refunded over
and over and over and over

00:25:27.290 --> 00:25:27.915
and over again?

00:25:27.915 --> 00:25:29.430
And you say, really cool.

00:25:29.430 --> 00:25:31.430
And then your bean counter
comes along and says,

00:25:31.430 --> 00:25:34.630
wait a minute,
it's 100% overhead.

00:25:34.630 --> 00:25:37.440
And suddenly, the bean counter
says, we can't help you out,

00:25:37.440 --> 00:25:39.850
because you're all overhead.

00:25:39.850 --> 00:25:42.670
Innovative ideas, I've
discovered in the charity

00:25:42.670 --> 00:25:45.190
world, with innovative
models, often

00:25:45.190 --> 00:25:48.130
struggle up against the
idea that with innovation,

00:25:48.130 --> 00:25:51.370
comes a roadblock from the
old ways of doing things.

00:25:54.330 --> 00:25:56.370
This is exactly the
type of PowerPoint slide

00:25:56.370 --> 00:25:57.800
you're not supposed to do.

00:25:57.800 --> 00:25:59.110
So I did it.

00:25:59.110 --> 00:26:00.640
Scan on the left hand side.

00:26:00.640 --> 00:26:02.140
And you're just going to
pick out one or two of them.

00:26:02.140 --> 00:26:04.515
These are emails that we've
received from people who say,

00:26:04.515 --> 00:26:06.630
I need help.

00:26:06.630 --> 00:26:08.310
On the right hand
hide, those are

00:26:08.310 --> 00:26:13.430
emails from people who
say, how can I help?

00:26:13.430 --> 00:26:15.230
This is America, side by side.

00:26:15.230 --> 00:26:17.980
50 people needing, help
42 million people saying,

00:26:17.980 --> 00:26:19.990
they can help.

00:26:19.990 --> 00:26:22.110
And all that's been
separating them

00:26:22.110 --> 00:26:24.262
has been the lack of
awareness that they already

00:26:24.262 --> 00:26:26.720
could be helping each other,
which is what AmpleHarvest.org

00:26:26.720 --> 00:26:29.050
has fixed, and continues to fix.

00:26:31.700 --> 00:26:34.780
Google has been an amazing
partner for AmpleHarvest.org.

00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:37.310
We're blessed and honored.

00:26:37.310 --> 00:26:40.450
And we want to-- just to
let you know how Googlers,

00:26:40.450 --> 00:26:43.460
how people here and people
watching can also help.

00:26:43.460 --> 00:26:45.800
One of the things is
AmpleHarvest.org/local,

00:26:45.800 --> 00:26:48.520
which is something open to
anybody and everybody across

00:26:48.520 --> 00:26:49.020
the country.

00:26:49.020 --> 00:26:50.440
The idea that there
are things you

00:26:50.440 --> 00:26:53.920
can do in your own community
to cement the AmpleHarvest.org

00:26:53.920 --> 00:26:55.030
model in your community.

00:26:55.030 --> 00:26:57.310
It takes a few hours of work.

00:26:57.310 --> 00:26:59.564
And it's a step by
step type of process.

00:26:59.564 --> 00:27:01.480
The second thing is
things specific to Google,

00:27:01.480 --> 00:27:03.480
including on that
Google page there,

00:27:03.480 --> 00:27:06.150
that fact that Google now
matches all donations to Hobbes

00:27:06.150 --> 00:27:09.260
AmpleHarvest.org, up to $6,000.

00:27:09.260 --> 00:27:12.150
I do speakers, and
also, we're looking

00:27:12.150 --> 00:27:13.570
for more engagement from people.

00:27:13.570 --> 00:27:16.090
So people who want to help
out have ideas, suggestions,

00:27:16.090 --> 00:27:18.790
whatever, I hope that
it's a type of thing that

00:27:18.790 --> 00:27:22.310
will move and inspire people.

00:27:22.310 --> 00:27:24.200
The heart behind
AmpleHarvest.org

00:27:24.200 --> 00:27:27.270
is the fact that
people are able to do

00:27:27.270 --> 00:27:29.280
things they thought
they couldn't do.

00:27:29.280 --> 00:27:31.850
Everybody wants to
be somebody special.

00:27:31.850 --> 00:27:35.660
I-- as a kid, I
wanted to be Superman.

00:27:35.660 --> 00:27:39.880
I used to fly into
my parents' bed.

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:43.140
We grow up, eventually
thinking that that's just

00:27:43.140 --> 00:27:44.110
not the way it is.

00:27:44.110 --> 00:27:45.700
We have real lives.

00:27:45.700 --> 00:27:49.130
The reality is that
AmpleHarvest.org's model

00:27:49.130 --> 00:27:50.964
is enabling anybody
to be the game

00:27:50.964 --> 00:27:52.255
changer in their own community.

00:27:52.255 --> 00:27:54.440
I was actually--
CNN had asked me

00:27:54.440 --> 00:27:56.960
at one point, what's it
feel like to be a hero?

00:27:56.960 --> 00:27:58.710
And I said, it's
really not about me.

00:27:58.710 --> 00:28:00.630
This is about 42
million people being

00:28:00.630 --> 00:28:02.290
the hero in their own community.

00:28:02.290 --> 00:28:06.630
When I was a kid, my mother
loved Leonard Bernstein,

00:28:06.630 --> 00:28:07.680
the conductor.

00:28:07.680 --> 00:28:09.590
And I never got it.

00:28:09.590 --> 00:28:12.534
I saw a guy with his back to
the audience, waving a stick.

00:28:12.534 --> 00:28:14.950
And I said to her, the musicians
are making all the music.

00:28:14.950 --> 00:28:17.560
This guy's waving a stick.

00:28:17.560 --> 00:28:19.480
AmpleHarvest.org is
waving the stick.

00:28:19.480 --> 00:28:21.620
But it's 42 million
people across the country

00:28:21.620 --> 00:28:24.590
could make the difference in
the future of the country,

00:28:24.590 --> 00:28:27.970
the health of the
children, the economy,

00:28:27.970 --> 00:28:30.299
and the welfare of the nation.

00:28:30.299 --> 00:28:32.090
So I want to thank you
all very, very much.

00:28:32.090 --> 00:28:34.380
And I think Kim and I are
gonna have a brief question

00:28:34.380 --> 00:28:34.880
and answer.

00:28:34.880 --> 00:28:37.040
And then open it up to
questions from all of you.

00:28:37.040 --> 00:28:38.336
Thank you.

00:28:38.336 --> 00:28:42.080
[APPLAUSE]

00:28:42.080 --> 00:28:43.760
KIM: Thanks, very, Gary.

00:28:43.760 --> 00:28:45.555
That was very inspiring.

00:28:45.555 --> 00:28:47.605
GARY OPPENHEIMER: Thank you.

00:28:47.605 --> 00:28:49.480
KIM: Now, I'm going to
ask you some intensely

00:28:49.480 --> 00:28:50.560
personal question.

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:51.640
GARY OPPENHEIMER: OK.

00:28:51.640 --> 00:28:52.940
KIM: They're not really.

00:28:52.940 --> 00:28:56.720
So you are a techie, a
gardener, an environmentalist.

00:28:56.720 --> 00:29:00.720
And then you created a
hunger food waste program.

00:29:00.720 --> 00:29:03.579
How did that happen?

00:29:03.579 --> 00:29:04.870
GARY OPPENHEIMER: I hate waste.

00:29:04.870 --> 00:29:06.860
Seriously, I grew up with,
finish what's on your plate.

00:29:06.860 --> 00:29:08.260
Kids are starving in Europe.

00:29:08.260 --> 00:29:11.887
And I saw the waste, and
I like solving problems.

00:29:11.887 --> 00:29:13.470
I mean, Vint had
talked about the fact

00:29:13.470 --> 00:29:17.270
that when I was a part of
MCI, I saw a company that

00:29:17.270 --> 00:29:20.000
had produced MCI Mail, a
really wonderful email service.

00:29:20.000 --> 00:29:22.333
But they weren't communicating
with their own customers.

00:29:22.333 --> 00:29:24.680
And I said, let me send
them out a newsletter.

00:29:24.680 --> 00:29:28.200
So I created the
newsletter, which

00:29:28.200 --> 00:29:31.250
maybe means I may have been one
of the first creators of spam.

00:29:31.250 --> 00:29:32.450
So my apologies.

00:29:32.450 --> 00:29:34.980
But the point was,
I see disconnects.

00:29:34.980 --> 00:29:36.520
And this was a clear disconnect.

00:29:36.520 --> 00:29:38.111
And it was an easy
one to fix too.

00:29:38.111 --> 00:29:39.610
Because nothing you
had to be built.

00:29:39.610 --> 00:29:41.680
It was just connecting the dots.

00:29:41.680 --> 00:29:43.438
And that's what got me to here.

00:29:43.438 --> 00:29:45.390
KIM: Cool.

00:29:45.390 --> 00:29:47.910
So since you've created
AmpleHarvest.org,

00:29:47.910 --> 00:29:51.661
what's been the most surprising
thing that you've learned?

00:29:51.661 --> 00:29:53.660
GARY OPPENHEIMER: What I
was just talking about.

00:29:53.660 --> 00:29:55.870
The difficulty
innovative charities

00:29:55.870 --> 00:29:57.650
have in getting support.

00:29:57.650 --> 00:29:59.220
I've seen lots of
other charities

00:29:59.220 --> 00:30:01.760
out there, with really great
ideas in all sorts of realms,

00:30:01.760 --> 00:30:04.820
struggle up against the fact
that they're doing new things.

00:30:04.820 --> 00:30:08.740
And the old way is
what's more accepted.

00:30:08.740 --> 00:30:11.800
Imagine for a minute, if you
built a better mouse trap,

00:30:11.800 --> 00:30:13.520
and you came to a
for-profit company,

00:30:13.520 --> 00:30:15.594
and they threw money
you to market it.

00:30:15.594 --> 00:30:17.760
And in a not for profit
world, the better mousetrap,

00:30:17.760 --> 00:30:20.770
they say, that's nice,
but we fund cats.

00:30:20.770 --> 00:30:21.870
This is in the problem.

00:30:21.870 --> 00:30:25.240
And I think it holds back the
improvement of our society.

00:30:25.240 --> 00:30:27.840
Because people who
have really good ideas

00:30:27.840 --> 00:30:29.266
get stymied, by
the fact that they

00:30:29.266 --> 00:30:30.890
can't be as impactful
as they could be.

00:30:30.890 --> 00:30:33.650
Just for lack of the old system
not catching up with them.

00:30:33.650 --> 00:30:37.970
There's a funding curve that
lags behind the innovation

00:30:37.970 --> 00:30:38.960
curve.

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:40.970
That's been very frustrating.

00:30:40.970 --> 00:30:43.060
KIM: Well, maybe you
answered my next question.

00:30:43.060 --> 00:30:45.594
Which was, what's your
biggest disappointment?

00:30:45.594 --> 00:30:48.010
GARY OPPENHEIMER: In that vein,
the biggest disappointment

00:30:48.010 --> 00:30:52.240
is, we couldn't have done
more than we've done so far.

00:30:52.240 --> 00:30:54.700
This model, and others
like it-- by the way,

00:30:54.700 --> 00:30:57.650
this model is a no-brainer
for the country.

00:30:57.650 --> 00:31:00.640
And if we had the
staff, and the resources

00:31:00.640 --> 00:31:03.770
we need, we could have--
as impactful as we've been,

00:31:03.770 --> 00:31:06.440
we could have been much more
impactful, many times over.

00:31:06.440 --> 00:31:09.010
I was actually approached at
a conference that I was at.

00:31:09.010 --> 00:31:10.760
And we went in the
room with the big boys.

00:31:10.760 --> 00:31:12.520
You know, Oxfam and Red Cross.

00:31:12.520 --> 00:31:14.930
And somebody said, how
much money do you need?

00:31:14.930 --> 00:31:16.759
And I said 500.

00:31:16.759 --> 00:31:17.800
And the guy said million?

00:31:17.800 --> 00:31:19.260
I said, no, thousand.

00:31:19.260 --> 00:31:20.910
And he just gave
me a blank stare.

00:31:20.910 --> 00:31:22.785
It was sort of like,
how can you do something

00:31:22.785 --> 00:31:25.450
like-- this-- that's been
the frustrating thing.

00:31:28.170 --> 00:31:30.162
We're going to deal with it.

00:31:30.162 --> 00:31:32.140
[DEEP EXHALE]

00:31:32.140 --> 00:31:33.720
KIM: How do you
think that changes?

00:31:33.720 --> 00:31:35.210
How do you make that change?

00:31:35.210 --> 00:31:39.342
I mean, change those minds,
to get out of that old system?

00:31:39.342 --> 00:31:41.344
GARY OPPENHEIMER: Oh, gosh.

00:31:41.344 --> 00:31:42.510
You keep banging away at it.

00:31:42.510 --> 00:31:43.490
You keep working at it.

00:31:43.490 --> 00:31:44.390
You don't give up.

00:31:44.390 --> 00:31:46.840
You keep proving that it works.

00:31:46.840 --> 00:31:48.650
You don't lose heart.

00:31:48.650 --> 00:31:53.472
And you take solace in
that you are doing good,

00:31:53.472 --> 00:31:54.930
and you're making
the world better.

00:31:54.930 --> 00:31:56.410
You're leaving the place
better than you found it,

00:31:56.410 --> 00:31:58.868
which I think is the heart of
what anybody should be doing,

00:31:58.868 --> 00:32:02.209
if they want to get
into doing good.

00:32:02.209 --> 00:32:04.000
KIM: You touched on it
a bit, in your talk.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:07.260
But what are your long term
hopes for AmpleHarvest.org?

00:32:07.260 --> 00:32:10.214
GARY OPPENHEIMER: I'd like
to put us out of business.

00:32:10.214 --> 00:32:12.130
It sounds the glib to
say, because you'd never

00:32:12.130 --> 00:32:13.755
hear many other
organizations say that.

00:32:13.755 --> 00:32:15.790
But when you think about
it for a moment-- when

00:32:15.790 --> 00:32:18.534
I was growing up, and
I'll be 62 in November.

00:32:18.534 --> 00:32:19.950
When I was growing
up, people were

00:32:19.950 --> 00:32:21.860
looking for money for
polio, and smallpox.

00:32:21.860 --> 00:32:24.810
Anybody here get a solicitation
for either of those lately?

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:25.470
No.

00:32:25.470 --> 00:32:27.350
They solved the problem,
and they went home.

00:32:27.350 --> 00:32:29.510
And I think a good charity
should find a problem,

00:32:29.510 --> 00:32:30.430
solve it, and go home.

00:32:30.430 --> 00:32:31.980
Because there's
lots of other places

00:32:31.980 --> 00:32:33.830
where money and
support is needed.

00:32:33.830 --> 00:32:37.370
And find the problem,
be able to fix it,

00:32:37.370 --> 00:32:40.290
or at least severely
diminish the problem.

00:32:40.290 --> 00:32:41.460
And be done with it.

00:32:41.460 --> 00:32:44.070
I think we can get to
a point in America,

00:32:44.070 --> 00:32:46.100
where everybody
looks at excess food

00:32:46.100 --> 00:32:48.556
the same way we all look
at, for example, old coats.

00:32:48.556 --> 00:32:51.180
You get an old coat, what's the
first thing that comes to mind?

00:32:51.180 --> 00:32:53.615
The Goodwill bin or
something else down the road.

00:32:53.615 --> 00:32:55.490
You drop it off, hoping
that somebody else is

00:32:55.490 --> 00:32:57.270
going to be able to use the coat
that you don't want anymore.

00:32:57.270 --> 00:32:59.070
We should be doing that
with all of our food.

00:32:59.070 --> 00:33:01.370
If we have more food-- and it's
not just gardeners, by the way.

00:33:01.370 --> 00:33:03.760
But if we have more food than
we could then we can use,

00:33:03.760 --> 00:33:05.861
we should be finding
ways, either not

00:33:05.861 --> 00:33:08.360
to have purchased and prepared
that much in the first place;

00:33:08.360 --> 00:33:10.520
or if we have it,
especially fresh food,

00:33:10.520 --> 00:33:12.770
get it to people who
really, really need it.

00:33:12.770 --> 00:33:17.240
It is a-- it's really--
forgive the pun,

00:33:17.240 --> 00:33:19.926
it's the low hanging fruit in
solving so many of our problems

00:33:19.926 --> 00:33:20.550
in our country.

00:33:20.550 --> 00:33:21.150
It really is.

00:33:21.150 --> 00:33:24.602
You get kids eating fresh food,
instead of processed food.

00:33:24.602 --> 00:33:26.810
You get the eating potatoes,
instead of potato chips.

00:33:26.810 --> 00:33:29.143
You get them to learn that
Apple's don't come pre-sliced

00:33:29.143 --> 00:33:30.080
in cellophane.

00:33:30.080 --> 00:33:33.380
You start to change the future
of how these kids grow up.

00:33:33.380 --> 00:33:36.980
And the diabetes
and obesity problems

00:33:36.980 --> 00:33:40.960
that is going to really hurt
this country gets thwarted.

00:33:40.960 --> 00:33:42.630
It's not hard to do.

00:33:42.630 --> 00:33:45.900
And it's not expensive at all.

00:33:45.900 --> 00:33:48.540
KIM: So you are touching
the world of food, waste,

00:33:48.540 --> 00:33:52.290
and hunger all the time,
what's the most difficult story

00:33:52.290 --> 00:33:53.500
that you've come across?

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:55.810
GARY OPPENHEIMER: Yeah.

00:33:55.810 --> 00:33:57.900
You saw that list
of emails I put up?

00:33:57.900 --> 00:33:59.110
That was a small sampling.

00:33:59.110 --> 00:34:01.526
We get emails from people all
the time saying, I'm hungry,

00:34:01.526 --> 00:34:03.214
I need help.

00:34:03.214 --> 00:34:03.880
Can you help us?

00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:04.800
And we can't actually.

00:34:04.800 --> 00:34:05.890
That's not our role.

00:34:05.890 --> 00:34:07.720
Remember, we're
fixing this pipeline,

00:34:07.720 --> 00:34:09.630
from the growers
to food pantries.

00:34:09.630 --> 00:34:11.159
We don't feed people.

00:34:11.159 --> 00:34:13.410
We're partnered with both
WhyHunger.org and the United

00:34:13.410 --> 00:34:13.909
Way.

00:34:13.909 --> 00:34:16.400
WhyHunger.org particularly,
is an amazing organization.

00:34:16.400 --> 00:34:18.969
And their job is to
connect a hungry family

00:34:18.969 --> 00:34:22.562
to food resource in
their own community.

00:34:22.562 --> 00:34:23.770
So we send them off that way.

00:34:23.770 --> 00:34:26.217
But by the way, each person
that does some of those emails

00:34:26.217 --> 00:34:28.300
gets a reply from myself
or somebody else, saying,

00:34:28.300 --> 00:34:29.550
we're really sorry.

00:34:29.550 --> 00:34:33.130
Here's where you can go.

00:34:33.130 --> 00:34:35.820
One woman wrote to me,
one of those letters.

00:34:35.820 --> 00:34:38.294
I'm having a difficult time.

00:34:38.294 --> 00:34:40.760
I can't feed my family,
my husband's ill.

00:34:40.760 --> 00:34:42.610
I don't remember
the details of it,

00:34:42.610 --> 00:34:45.920
but what blew me off was
when I saw the bottom.

00:34:45.920 --> 00:34:47.850
She was active duty US Navy.

00:34:47.850 --> 00:34:49.940
That hurt.

00:34:49.940 --> 00:34:50.810
That shouldn't be.

00:34:50.810 --> 00:34:53.699
Sorry, I get choked
up about that still.

00:34:53.699 --> 00:34:55.809
That was tough.

00:34:55.809 --> 00:34:57.100
That was the toughest probably.

00:34:59.690 --> 00:35:02.730
But that's what's going
on in the country.

00:35:02.730 --> 00:35:05.980
KIM: Can you tell us
one of the best stories?

00:35:05.980 --> 00:35:07.111
GARY OPPENHEIMER: Yeah.

00:35:07.111 --> 00:35:08.610
I actually have it
on my thing here.

00:35:08.610 --> 00:35:11.210
I want to read it, because
it's that good a story.

00:35:11.210 --> 00:35:12.920
This was an email
that I'd gotten,

00:35:12.920 --> 00:35:16.710
and I hope it's still hear.

00:35:16.710 --> 00:35:24.390
A woman who was raising a bunch
of kids, and she had let's see,

00:35:24.390 --> 00:35:26.100
here we go-- I'm
gonna just read this.

00:35:26.100 --> 00:35:27.580
So you can see what
this-- this was just

00:35:27.580 --> 00:35:28.860
a wonderful,
wonderful short story.

00:35:28.860 --> 00:35:29.859
I'm the mother of seven.

00:35:29.859 --> 00:35:32.756
15 grandchildren and
others, that I'm mom to.

00:35:32.756 --> 00:35:34.380
We have a garden,
that we plant for us.

00:35:34.380 --> 00:35:36.730
But it's not enough.

00:35:36.730 --> 00:35:38.900
She got the kids planting food.

00:35:38.900 --> 00:35:41.310
She got the kids involved
in the gardening.

00:35:41.310 --> 00:35:45.690
And the kids got really, really
excited about seeing the food

00:35:45.690 --> 00:35:46.704
growing.

00:35:46.704 --> 00:35:49.370
If you could see the garden, the
faces of the babies when they--

00:35:49.370 --> 00:35:51.940
and quote, unquote, 'babies,'--
when they go out and the food

00:35:51.940 --> 00:35:54.273
and the veggies for supper,
it was so wonderful for them

00:35:54.273 --> 00:35:55.202
to get fresh veggies.

00:35:55.202 --> 00:35:56.160
That was good for them.

00:35:56.160 --> 00:36:00.430
One of my babies last year
ate every tomato on one plant.

00:36:00.430 --> 00:36:02.560
These were his tomatoes.

00:36:02.560 --> 00:36:05.510
The mom said he hated them, but
sure enough changed her mind

00:36:05.510 --> 00:36:07.260
when he was eating them, here.

00:36:07.260 --> 00:36:10.380
We have lemon trees, pineapple
trees, et cetera, et cetera.

00:36:10.380 --> 00:36:13.260
Kids react to the
fact-- when they

00:36:13.260 --> 00:36:17.370
can taste what a real piece
of produce tastes like,

00:36:17.370 --> 00:36:18.120
it changes them.

00:36:18.120 --> 00:36:20.760
And this kid, whoever this
kid is, is changed for life.

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:23.800
And this happens to millions
of kids across the country.

00:36:23.800 --> 00:36:24.690
That's great.

00:36:24.690 --> 00:36:27.880
That offsets the Navy lady
story, many times over.

00:36:27.880 --> 00:36:28.897
It's really nice.

00:36:28.897 --> 00:36:29.980
KIM: That's a great story.

