00:39:52.984 --> 00:39:53.650
AUDIENCE: Hello.

00:39:53.650 --> 00:39:54.525
GARY OPPENHEIMER: Hi.

00:39:54.525 --> 00:39:56.530
AUDIENCE: To ask a beam
counter-y question,

00:39:56.530 --> 00:39:59.360
do you have an estimate of
the dollar value of the goods

00:39:59.360 --> 00:40:04.140
that you've facilitated, moving
from growers to the food banks?

00:40:04.140 --> 00:40:05.050
GARY OPPENHEIMER: No.

00:40:05.050 --> 00:40:06.300
That's a really good question.

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:09.020
And I appreciate you leading
in with the bean counter type

00:40:09.020 --> 00:40:09.520
thing.

00:40:09.520 --> 00:40:13.390
But it's-- honestly, the dollar
value is not as important

00:40:13.390 --> 00:40:15.030
as the nutritional value.

00:40:15.030 --> 00:40:18.470
Because the nutritional value
represents a multiplier effect.

00:40:18.470 --> 00:40:21.640
I'm making up a number; if
I donate $100 of tomatoes,

00:40:21.640 --> 00:40:26.100
I've benefited the
community by $100, frankly.

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:29.990
But if I donate $100 worth
of health, the long term

00:40:29.990 --> 00:40:31.350
impact of that.

00:40:31.350 --> 00:40:34.030
In terms of the reduction
of future health issues,

00:40:34.030 --> 00:40:37.060
many times magnifies that over.

00:40:37.060 --> 00:40:38.560
From a metrics
perspective, I should

00:40:38.560 --> 00:40:41.597
say that the discussion that's
always been with food has been,

00:40:41.597 --> 00:40:42.930
how many pounds, how many meals?

00:40:42.930 --> 00:40:44.790
I touched on that.

00:40:44.790 --> 00:40:47.880
In the fresh food realm,
poundage doesn't really

00:40:47.880 --> 00:40:48.860
make a lot of sense.

00:40:48.860 --> 00:40:50.443
How are you going
to compare donations

00:40:50.443 --> 00:40:51.980
of watermelon and spinach?

00:40:51.980 --> 00:40:55.630
The same weight of the two,
spinach is immensely more help,

00:40:55.630 --> 00:40:58.890
beneficial to the community and
the country then watermelon is.

00:40:58.890 --> 00:41:00.730
One of the projects
we have lined up,

00:41:00.730 --> 00:41:02.860
and the Clinton people
would like to see us do it,

00:41:02.860 --> 00:41:05.010
is the Community
Nutritional Index.

00:41:05.010 --> 00:41:07.780
The this is a model that
I have in my mind, that

00:41:07.780 --> 00:41:11.010
takes what I used to
see in PC Magazine,

00:41:11.010 --> 00:41:13.710
in my geeky days, which is
how you sort of measured

00:41:13.710 --> 00:41:16.255
the relative value of
this brand of computer,

00:41:16.255 --> 00:41:19.556
versus that brand of computer,
and apply it to fresh food.

00:41:19.556 --> 00:41:21.180
Which would then
start to get us closer

00:41:21.180 --> 00:41:22.560
to the financial
question you're asking.

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:24.480
Because under that
scenario, we can then

00:41:24.480 --> 00:41:26.800
realize that a
pound of watermelon,

00:41:26.800 --> 00:41:28.420
is equal to this much of this.

00:41:28.420 --> 00:41:31.670
And look at the individual
macro and micro nutrient.

00:41:31.670 --> 00:41:34.840
That can then get translated
to a dollar value.

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:37.120
One of the informal advisers
for AmpleHarvest.org

00:41:37.120 --> 00:41:38.920
is Rear Admiral Dr.
Susan Blumenthal,

00:41:38.920 --> 00:41:40.400
who is the former
Assistant Surgeon

00:41:40.400 --> 00:41:41.608
General of the United States.

00:41:41.608 --> 00:41:45.910
So we have access to a
wealth of medical input,

00:41:45.910 --> 00:41:49.490
and health ideas
along those lines.

00:41:49.490 --> 00:41:54.340
We've documented informally,
many, many tens of millions

00:41:54.340 --> 00:41:56.870
of dollars of-- tens
of millions of pounds,

00:41:56.870 --> 00:41:58.920
I'm sorry-- of food
having come in.

00:41:58.920 --> 00:42:01.510
Why can't we give
you an exact number?

00:42:01.510 --> 00:42:03.060
If you remember
that big green line

00:42:03.060 --> 00:42:05.090
that came from the
gardener to the pantry?

00:42:05.090 --> 00:42:06.594
The food doesn't
pass through us.

00:42:06.594 --> 00:42:08.510
We don't touch the food,
there's no logistics.

00:42:08.510 --> 00:42:10.470
We ask people to tell
us what you've donated.

00:42:10.470 --> 00:42:12.136
But the other side
is the food pantries,

00:42:12.136 --> 00:42:13.920
are really lousy at metrics.

00:42:13.920 --> 00:42:15.360
They don't have scales.

00:42:15.360 --> 00:42:18.310
We ask them how much
food, we get bags.

00:42:18.310 --> 00:42:19.200
We get boxes.

00:42:19.200 --> 00:42:20.190
We get bushels.

00:42:20.190 --> 00:42:24.190
We get-- one food pantry--
we did an early survey,

00:42:24.190 --> 00:42:26.495
and we said how many
pounds of food did you get,

00:42:26.495 --> 00:42:27.370
did you possibly get?

00:42:27.370 --> 00:42:30.620
This is probably in 2010, we
were less than a year old.

00:42:30.620 --> 00:42:33.500
They said 9 million pounds.

00:42:33.500 --> 00:42:35.120
We were seeing
numbers like none.

00:42:35.120 --> 00:42:36.020
500 pounds.

00:42:36.020 --> 00:42:36.690
25 pounds.

00:42:36.690 --> 00:42:37.210
9 million?

00:42:37.210 --> 00:42:40.710
I call this person up,
and said, is this a typo?

00:42:40.710 --> 00:42:41.485
They said no.

00:42:41.485 --> 00:42:41.985
No.

00:42:41.985 --> 00:42:44.070
A farmer heard about us,
through AmpleHarvest.org,

00:42:44.070 --> 00:42:45.736
and started bringing
truckloads of food.

00:42:48.200 --> 00:42:49.230
How do you measure that?

00:42:49.230 --> 00:42:51.630
Other then, it's
just-- I was stunned.

00:42:51.630 --> 00:42:52.784
I was thrilled.

