00:45:18.060 --> 00:45:21.860
Producepedia is
really very important.

00:45:21.860 --> 00:45:26.030
This sort of came on my radar
when a teacher wrote to me.

00:45:26.030 --> 00:45:27.670
We were probably
about a year old.

00:45:27.670 --> 00:45:31.620
She said she brought an
apple, a cucumber and a-- I

00:45:31.620 --> 00:45:35.130
think it was a pare or
something, into her classroom.

00:45:35.130 --> 00:45:37.269
And most the kids have no
idea what a cucumber was.

00:45:37.269 --> 00:45:39.060
And I suspect they knew
what the apple was,

00:45:39.060 --> 00:45:40.476
because they
probably had iPhones.

00:45:40.476 --> 00:45:44.290
But really people are
disconnected from the food.

00:45:44.290 --> 00:45:45.790
And so the idea
behind Producepedia,

00:45:45.790 --> 00:45:48.080
what we want to
build, is something

00:45:48.080 --> 00:45:53.400
whereby we will have a database
of all the foods people grow.

00:45:53.400 --> 00:45:56.450
And I'm not just saying apples
and carrots and oranges,

00:45:56.450 --> 00:46:00.030
I'm talking about very,
very, very granularly.

00:46:00.030 --> 00:46:01.560
I grow tomatoes.

00:46:01.560 --> 00:46:03.535
Now, we all have tomatoes.

00:46:03.535 --> 00:46:05.660
You have the red tomatoes,
and the yellow tomatoes,

00:46:05.660 --> 00:46:07.140
and the cherry tomatoes.

00:46:07.140 --> 00:46:10.030
And there are-- anybody
see an Icelandic tomato?

00:46:10.030 --> 00:46:10.530
No.

00:46:10.530 --> 00:46:11.860
They're white. krim tomatoes?

00:46:11.860 --> 00:46:12.550
Black.

00:46:12.550 --> 00:46:15.000
So if I were to bring
Icelandic tomatoes into a food

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:17.720
pantry, or a krim one, which
is black, people would say,

00:46:17.720 --> 00:46:19.320
I don't know.

00:46:19.320 --> 00:46:22.760
The idea behind Producepedia
is to create a print out,

00:46:22.760 --> 00:46:24.490
a simple print
out, that not only

00:46:24.490 --> 00:46:27.000
says what the food is, with
a picture, inside, outside.

00:46:27.000 --> 00:46:28.750
But some basic
information about it,

00:46:28.750 --> 00:46:30.430
so that the pantry
and the people,

00:46:30.430 --> 00:46:31.570
they would know what
they're getting.

00:46:31.570 --> 00:46:32.528
And what to do with it.

00:46:32.528 --> 00:46:33.520
Do you eat it raw?

00:46:33.520 --> 00:46:34.240
Do you cook it?

00:46:34.240 --> 00:46:36.240
Or whatever.

00:46:36.240 --> 00:46:37.770
So the food wouldn't
go to waste.

00:46:37.770 --> 00:46:39.395
I grew purple carrots
one year, my wife

00:46:39.395 --> 00:46:42.300
didn't know what to
do with the stuff.

00:46:42.300 --> 00:46:45.350
So you can imagine what
it's like on a larger scale.

00:46:45.350 --> 00:46:48.830
The programs are lined
up, that I want to build.

00:46:48.830 --> 00:46:51.360
The staffing is what's
needed to actually expand

00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:54.650
AmpleHarvest.org, to its
full potential impact.

00:46:54.650 --> 00:46:56.530
Just to give you an
idea of-- the staff

00:46:56.530 --> 00:46:58.720
consists of one
person whose full time

00:46:58.720 --> 00:47:00.210
work is to work
with the pantries.

00:47:00.210 --> 00:47:03.750
And every pantry that
signs up, all 7,000,

00:47:03.750 --> 00:47:05.360
have been vetted by this person.

00:47:05.360 --> 00:47:07.065
Or by somebody in her position.

00:47:07.065 --> 00:47:08.940
We want to make sure,
when a pantry signs up,

00:47:08.940 --> 00:47:09.990
that it's really a pantry.

00:47:09.990 --> 00:47:12.365
And if it fits our criteria
of giving food away for free,

00:47:12.365 --> 00:47:13.630
and being a nonprofit.

00:47:13.630 --> 00:47:15.990
That it's not something
it shouldn't really be.

00:47:15.990 --> 00:47:17.660
So we're verifying each one.

00:47:17.660 --> 00:47:19.540
The other one, she's
involved in reaching out

00:47:19.540 --> 00:47:22.123
to the gardeners across America,
saying the solution to hunger

00:47:22.123 --> 00:47:23.550
is in your backyard.

00:47:23.550 --> 00:47:25.740
I'm there, sort of
running the whole thing,

00:47:25.740 --> 00:47:27.520
and trying to push
the message out.

00:47:27.520 --> 00:47:28.900
And we have a part time admin.

00:47:28.900 --> 00:47:32.480
We need a few more people to
do the stuff, the technology,

00:47:32.480 --> 00:47:34.630
and all the other pieces
that are in there.

00:47:34.630 --> 00:47:36.480
But Producepedia would
be the final step

00:47:36.480 --> 00:47:38.146
in making sure that
people at the pantry

00:47:38.146 --> 00:47:39.630
make the best use of the food.

00:47:39.630 --> 00:47:42.320
The gleaningharvest.org,
as I said,

00:47:42.320 --> 00:47:44.540
will dwarf
AmpleHarvest.org, in terms

00:47:44.540 --> 00:47:47.450
of the amount of food
coming into the system.

00:47:47.450 --> 00:47:50.600
If you look at the end NRDC
reports-- and if, by the way,

00:47:50.600 --> 00:47:53.160
anybody who wants to
see the presentation,

00:47:53.160 --> 00:47:55.822
if you go to
AmpleHarvest.org/googletechtalk,

00:47:55.822 --> 00:47:57.530
it'll be a PDF you
can freely downloaded.

00:47:57.530 --> 00:48:00.550
It's available right now.

00:48:00.550 --> 00:48:04.250
The gleaningharvest.org,
is going to connect people

00:48:04.250 --> 00:48:06.234
to organizations they
never we knew existed.

00:48:06.234 --> 00:48:08.150
I go into places all the
time full of foodies,

00:48:08.150 --> 00:48:10.524
and I say do you know gleaners
or gleaning organizations?

00:48:10.524 --> 00:48:11.992
Many people don't.

00:48:11.992 --> 00:48:14.200
It's in the Old Testament,
Book of Ruth, Deuteronomy,

00:48:14.200 --> 00:48:16.224
you know, leave the
food in the corners,

00:48:16.224 --> 00:48:17.390
in the edges of your fields.

00:48:17.390 --> 00:48:19.050
Don't pick up what
you drop, it's

00:48:19.050 --> 00:48:20.980
for the poor, the
widow, and the traveler.

00:48:20.980 --> 00:48:22.750
We have organizations
in this country that

00:48:22.750 --> 00:48:25.110
are volunteers, people, and
most important, insurance,

00:48:25.110 --> 00:48:28.450
who will come to farm or
your community garden,

00:48:28.450 --> 00:48:31.520
harvest the food, and get it to
the people who really need it.

00:48:31.520 --> 00:48:34.190
Except nobody knows they exist.

00:48:34.190 --> 00:48:36.424
We want to build the bridge,
built on Google Maps,

00:48:36.424 --> 00:48:37.840
that's going to
connect the people

00:48:37.840 --> 00:48:40.423
with these organizations, bring
them together, and again, once

00:48:40.423 --> 00:48:42.056
that connection's
made, its permanent.

00:48:42.056 --> 00:48:43.680
And then when after
the farmer harvests

00:48:43.680 --> 00:48:46.525
the fields, and x percent of
the celery, of the potatoes

00:48:46.525 --> 00:48:48.900
are left, or the apple orchard,
and a whole lot of apples

00:48:48.900 --> 00:48:51.020
are left down,
volunteers can come in,

00:48:51.020 --> 00:48:53.760
and that food gets
into the system.

00:48:53.760 --> 00:48:57.280
I went to visit a food bank
in Israel's assistance called

00:48:57.280 --> 00:49:00.280
Leket Israel, and I was--
they have magnificent gleaning

00:49:00.280 --> 00:49:00.780
operations.

00:49:00.780 --> 00:49:03.290
It's the gold standard
for the world.

00:49:03.290 --> 00:49:06.670
And I was stunned.

00:49:06.670 --> 00:49:12.060
Nothing in that food
bank was processed food,

00:49:12.060 --> 00:49:12.990
with one exception.

00:49:12.990 --> 00:49:16.590
Israelis have this thing about
this thick chocolate spread.

00:49:16.590 --> 00:49:18.800
But everything else
was fresh produce

00:49:18.800 --> 00:49:21.425
that have been gleaned from
farms across the country.

00:49:21.425 --> 00:49:22.800
And that's getting
into a system.

00:49:22.800 --> 00:49:24.745
And we can and should
be doing it here.

00:49:24.745 --> 00:49:25.790
And gleaningharvest.org
is exactly where

00:49:25.790 --> 00:49:27.670
I want to get that
particular thing done.

