the Clinton Foundation's Health

00:51:10.190 --> 00:51:11.360
Matter Initiative.

00:51:11.360 --> 00:51:12.410
You keep at it.

00:51:12.410 --> 00:51:15.210
And honestly, if you're
not succeeding here,

00:51:15.210 --> 00:51:17.600
just go another way.

00:51:17.600 --> 00:51:19.194
The heart of
AmpleHarvest.org actually

00:51:19.194 --> 00:51:21.360
is, when you hit a roadblock,
take a different path.

00:51:21.360 --> 00:51:23.902
Which is strangely enough, the
underpinnings of the internet.

00:51:23.902 --> 00:51:25.568
I mean, when you're
sending information,

00:51:25.568 --> 00:51:27.700
if this node is down,
route it around that node.

00:51:27.700 --> 00:51:29.120
It's not really any different.

00:51:29.120 --> 00:51:32.920
The other thing is, and this
is something that the man that

00:51:32.920 --> 00:51:36.060
Vint and I both, I guess worked
under at MCI-- his saying,

00:51:36.060 --> 00:51:38.265
which I've adopted, is
to do the impossible,

00:51:38.265 --> 00:51:40.310
you must first believe it isn't.

00:51:40.310 --> 00:51:41.684
His name is Bob [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:41.684 --> 00:51:43.850
I have an ashtray with that
on there, I treasure it.

00:51:43.850 --> 00:51:46.810
It's really, really
important that if you believe

00:51:46.810 --> 00:51:48.810
in something, whether
it's in the not for profit

00:51:48.810 --> 00:51:51.300
or the for-profit
world, stick to it.

00:51:51.300 --> 00:51:52.190
Be true to it.

00:51:52.190 --> 00:51:55.520
If it's the right
thing, it'll happen.

00:51:55.520 --> 00:51:58.286
It may not happen as big or
as gloriously as you wanted.

00:51:58.286 --> 00:52:00.660
In my case, this happened far
bigger, and more gloriously

00:52:00.660 --> 00:52:01.900
than I had ever expected.

00:52:01.900 --> 00:52:03.960
I mean, I'm an aging geek.

00:52:03.960 --> 00:52:06.080
I have no background
in the nonprofit world.

00:52:06.080 --> 00:52:10.710
And I'm at a point now
where I'm talking to you.

00:52:10.710 --> 00:52:11.954
I've met two presidents.

00:52:11.954 --> 00:52:13.620
I go around the country
giving speeches.

00:52:13.620 --> 00:52:15.119
There's been a long
litany of things

00:52:15.119 --> 00:52:18.450
that six years ago, I
would've never expected.

00:52:18.450 --> 00:52:24.630
The thing to do is also to
[DEEP EXHALE] find people

00:52:24.630 --> 00:52:27.670
who believe the
same thing you do.

00:52:27.670 --> 00:52:30.214
Invite them, partner
like crazy, by the way.

00:52:30.214 --> 00:52:31.130
Stick to your mission.

00:52:31.130 --> 00:52:32.080
That's super critical.

00:52:32.080 --> 00:52:33.250
There's something
called mission creep.

00:52:33.250 --> 00:52:34.630
Never go down that path.

00:52:34.630 --> 00:52:37.270
If you believe-- if your mission
is to do this, stick to it,

00:52:37.270 --> 00:52:38.860
and find partners
to do nearby things.

00:52:38.860 --> 00:52:40.960
But don't drift
into their stuff.

00:52:40.960 --> 00:52:41.660
We've done that.

00:52:41.660 --> 00:52:44.070
We don't help people get food.

00:52:44.070 --> 00:52:47.130
We go to WhyHunger or National
Hunger Hotline, or United Way.

00:52:47.130 --> 00:52:48.440
That's their job.

00:52:48.440 --> 00:52:50.370
We don't tell
people how to grow.

00:52:50.370 --> 00:52:53.610
National Gardening Association
does a great job, as do others.

00:52:53.610 --> 00:52:57.480
We are that connector between
the food in the community,

00:52:57.480 --> 00:52:59.060
and the need in the community.

00:52:59.060 --> 00:53:00.810
And we're educating,
encouraging,

00:53:00.810 --> 00:53:03.390
and enabling millions
of growers to donate.

00:53:03.390 --> 00:53:05.880
By the result of doing
that-- I hate the expression,

00:53:05.880 --> 00:53:08.950
but we own the
space that were in.

00:53:08.950 --> 00:53:10.540
People are using
us as a resource

00:53:10.540 --> 00:53:12.000
to do their different
things, which is great.

00:53:12.000 --> 00:53:13.760
There's a new student
group in Florida

00:53:13.760 --> 00:53:14.920
that's doing a food
recovery thing,

00:53:14.920 --> 00:53:16.836
and they're using
AmpleHarvest.org's resources

00:53:16.836 --> 00:53:18.170
to help them do their stuff.

00:53:18.170 --> 00:53:19.904
And our model is now
with our systems,

00:53:19.904 --> 00:53:21.320
being replicated
around the world.

00:53:21.320 --> 00:53:25.530
I've met with people in--
well, I shouldn't say in.

00:53:25.530 --> 00:53:27.060
I've been to Greece and Israel.

00:53:27.060 --> 00:53:29.970
But all this I've either
emailed, Skype or whatever,

00:53:29.970 --> 00:53:34.860
England, Poland, the UK, South
Africa, Japan, New Zealand,

00:53:34.860 --> 00:53:37.400
Australia, I missing a few.

00:53:37.400 --> 00:53:40.140
And we're making this
information freely available.

00:53:40.140 --> 00:53:42.680
This is how it
works, in America.

00:53:42.680 --> 00:53:45.430
Make it work in your system,
in your language, your culture,

00:53:45.430 --> 00:53:47.580
whatever, in your country.

00:53:47.580 --> 00:53:49.719
The food waste issue is
not an American problem.

00:53:49.719 --> 00:53:51.760
I like the way Tristram
Stuart brilliantly shows,

00:53:51.760 --> 00:53:53.440
it is a global problem.

00:53:53.440 --> 00:53:56.060
But there's also a
global opportunity.

00:53:56.060 --> 00:53:58.750
We've got a model
that was perfectly fit

00:53:58.750 --> 00:54:00.800
for the American food
distribution network.

00:54:00.800 --> 00:54:01.780
It was built for that.

00:54:04.810 --> 00:54:07.590
And also, one other thing, and
I should've said this earlier,

00:54:07.590 --> 00:54:09.690
so I'm going to say it now.

00:54:09.690 --> 00:54:12.624
Think about other areas where
you can influence things,

00:54:12.624 --> 00:54:14.040
in the work you're
doing, that you

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:15.020
wouldn't have thought about.

00:54:15.020 --> 00:54:17.240
I built AmpleHarvest.org
with something called 'just

00:54:17.240 --> 00:54:18.890
in time' inventory.

00:54:18.890 --> 00:54:20.724
And in manufacturing,
just in time inventory

00:54:20.724 --> 00:54:23.223
is something-- having pieces
arrive just when you need them.

00:54:23.223 --> 00:54:24.720
When Boeing's
making an airplane,

00:54:24.720 --> 00:54:26.200
they have the wings
arrive just when it's

00:54:26.200 --> 00:54:27.410
ready to be attached
to the fuselage.

00:54:27.410 --> 00:54:28.840
It's not sitting on the side.

00:54:28.840 --> 00:54:32.090
So things come just in time.

00:54:32.090 --> 00:54:34.710
AmpleHarvest.org harvest
was built in a way in which,

00:54:34.710 --> 00:54:39.180
we tell the pantries to tell
the growers when to come.

00:54:39.180 --> 00:54:40.870
And by the way, this
one little speck

00:54:40.870 --> 00:54:42.710
changes a whole bunch of things.

00:54:42.710 --> 00:54:44.460
We told the pantries,
tell the growers

00:54:44.460 --> 00:54:46.600
to come an hour or two
before the clients come

00:54:46.600 --> 00:54:48.240
to pick up the food.

00:54:48.240 --> 00:54:50.040
Now what happens as
a result of that?

00:54:50.040 --> 00:54:53.990
Well, number one is the food
comes in, stays a few hours,

00:54:53.990 --> 00:54:54.630
and goes out.

00:54:54.630 --> 00:54:56.800
We've eliminated the need for
refrigeration and storage.

00:54:56.800 --> 00:54:58.450
That was a huge
impediment for pantries

00:54:58.450 --> 00:54:59.880
nationwide to take fresh food.

00:54:59.880 --> 00:55:01.050
We have no place to store
it, we have no place

00:55:01.050 --> 00:55:01.830
to refrigerate it.

00:55:01.830 --> 00:55:05.030
In, out same day basis,
no refrigeration.

00:55:05.030 --> 00:55:07.010
But there's an ethical
component to it too.

00:55:07.010 --> 00:55:09.750
In our society,
it's entirely likely

00:55:09.750 --> 00:55:11.647
that I'm growing more
food than I can use,

00:55:11.647 --> 00:55:14.230
and you're my next door neighbor
who has fallen on hard times.

00:55:14.230 --> 00:55:15.660
And you're going
to a food pantry,

00:55:15.660 --> 00:55:17.249
you're kind of
humiliated as it is.

00:55:17.249 --> 00:55:19.540
You wish you could take care
of your own family better,

00:55:19.540 --> 00:55:20.440
and you didn't need
to use a pantry.

00:55:20.440 --> 00:55:22.370
You shouldn't feel
that way, but you do.

00:55:22.370 --> 00:55:24.120
The worst thing is for
me to be showing up

00:55:24.120 --> 00:55:26.660
with my basket of
food, you showing up

00:55:26.660 --> 00:55:28.680
to pick up your thing,
and I'm embarrassed,

00:55:28.680 --> 00:55:30.150
and you're humiliated.

00:55:30.150 --> 00:55:33.610
By separating by time,
I'm coming in a few hours

00:55:33.610 --> 00:55:35.690
before you, I know it's
going to my community,

00:55:35.690 --> 00:55:36.929
but I don't know who.

00:55:36.929 --> 00:55:38.470
You know it came
from your community,

00:55:38.470 --> 00:55:40.360
but you don't know who.

00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:42.770
The ethics in that's
really, really important.

00:55:42.770 --> 00:55:45.830
The food moves, they use
no refrigeration, storage,

00:55:45.830 --> 00:55:49.710
and our relationship has
nothing to this whole thing.

00:55:49.710 --> 00:55:51.320
You can find other ways to make.

00:55:51.320 --> 00:55:53.870
And those things alone
excite other people.

00:55:53.870 --> 00:55:57.780
That gets people informed--
wow, I can do these things too.

00:55:57.780 --> 00:56:00.170
And the last thing I would
say is, share your knowledge.

00:56:00.170 --> 00:56:03.100
I love talking at universities.

00:56:03.100 --> 00:56:05.240
Not because I like to
talk, although I do.

00:56:05.240 --> 00:56:06.590
It's because I like to listen.

00:56:06.590 --> 00:56:09.080
And the students come back to
me, some really great ideas

00:56:09.080 --> 00:56:10.538
and really, really
great questions.

00:56:10.538 --> 00:56:13.049
And some of them have
jazzed up things,

00:56:13.049 --> 00:56:14.840
and we've added things
on AmpleHarvest.org.

00:56:14.840 --> 00:56:17.240
Somebody came to us with an
idea that we never thought

00:56:17.240 --> 00:56:19.690
about, and fits, and we do it.

00:56:19.690 --> 00:56:20.730
So share the knowledge.

00:56:20.730 --> 00:56:21.440
Share the information.

00:56:21.440 --> 00:56:22.350
Share your successes.

00:56:22.350 --> 00:56:23.680
Share your failures.

00:56:23.680 --> 00:56:25.600
And I'm happy to
talk you further

00:56:25.600 --> 00:56:29.822
about it, if you want--
whatever your endeavors is.

00:56:29.822 --> 00:56:30.530
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:56:30.530 --> 00:56:31.730
GARY OPPENHEIMER: Thank you.

